'''Webley John Hauxhurst, Jr.''' (1809-1874) was a pioneer in [[Oregon Country]]. He helped build the first grist mill in Oregon, participated in the [[Willamette Cattle Company]], and was a participant at the Champoeg meeting where he voted for the creation of a provisional government.

==Early life==
Hauxhurst was born in [[Brooklyn, New York]] in 1806.<ref name="Champoeg"/> As a young man he became a sailor, and later deserted his ship while in California. He spent three years there in Monterey working as a carpenter before leaving.<ref>[http://www.upa.pdx.edu/IMS/currentprojects/TAHv3/Content/Boundaries/OR%20Emigrants%201838-1840.pdf The Oregon Territory: Inhabitants Prior To 1839]</ref> 

==Oregon==
Webley John Hauxhurst traveled to [[Oregon]] in 1834. He came with [[Ewing Young]] and [[Hall J. Kelley]] from [[California]], arriving at [[Fort Vancouver]] on the [[Columbia River]] on October 17.<ref name="Champoeg">{{cite book
  | last = Hussey
  | first = John A.
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Champoeg: Place of Transition, A Disputed History
  | work = 
  | publisher = Oregon Historical Society
  | year = 1967
  | doi =  
  | id =  }}
</ref> The next year, 1835, he helped to build the first grist mill in the [[Willamette Valley]] to mill grain.<ref name="Champoeg"/> This mill he would later sell to [[Thomas McKay]], the stepson of  Doctor [[John McLoughlin]], the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] Chief Factor at Fort Vancouver.<ref name="Champoeg"/> Hauxhurst was also an investor in the [[Willamette Cattle Company]] in 1837 that brought over 600 head of cattle to Oregon from California.<ref name="OR406">
{{cite journal
  | last =
  | first =
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Wallamette Settlement Articles of Agreement
  | journal = Provisional and Territorial Records
  | volume = 
  | issue = 
  | pages = 406
  | publisher = Oregon Provisional Government
  | date = 1-13-1837
  | url =
  | doi =
  | id =
  | accessdate =  }}
</ref> Originally, he was also going to accompany the group and help drive the [[cattle]] to Oregon, but changed his mind after the ship [[Loriot (ship)|Loriot]] was delayed in sailing.<ref>[http://www.oregon.com/history/oregon_trail_timeline_1831-1840.cfm Oregon Trail Timeline]</ref>

On Saturday, February 28, 1837, Webley Hauxhurst was married.<ref name=lee>[http://www.oregonvos.net/~clenzen/methodist.html Methodist Church Records in Oregon]</ref> The Reverend [[Jason Lee (missionary)|Jason Lee]] of the [[Methodist Mission]] then located at Mission Bottom married Miss Mary to Webley at the Mission house.<ref name=lee/> Mary was a [[Native American]] from the [[Yamhill]] tribe.<ref name="Champoeg"/> Hauxhurst would then became the mission's first white convert.<ref name="Champoeg"/>

In 1843 in the aftermath of Young<U+2019>s death in 1841, the settlers of the region began discussions about forming a government as a continuation of the [[Champoeg Meetings]].<ref name="OrTr1">{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Beginnings of Self-Government
  | work = Settling the Oregon Country 
  | publisher = End of the Oregon Trail Interpretive Center
  | date = 
  | url =  http://www.endoftheoregontrail.org/road2oregon/sa31provgovt.html
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2007-03-26 }}
</ref> Then in May of that year, there was large meeting at [[Champoeg, Oregon|Champoeg]] on the 2nd where a vote was taken on whether or not to form a government.<ref name="Champoeg"/> Hauxhurst participated in this meeting and voted for the creation of the [[Provisional Government of Oregon]] that would last until 1849.<ref name="BlueBook">{{cite book
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Oregon Blue Book: 1917-1918
  | work = 
  | publisher = Oregon Secretary of State
  | year = 1917
  | doi =  
  | id =  }}
</ref> In March of 1844 he enlisted with the [[Oregon Rangers]], a volunteer militia, as part of the Provisional Government's attempt to protect settlers from possible [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] attacks.<ref name="Brown">Brown, J. Henry (1892). ''Political History of Oregon: Provisional Government.'' The Lewis & Dryden Printing Co.: Portland.</ref>

==Later life==
After selling the grist mill, he moved to the Mill Creek area of what is now [[Salem, Oregon]].<ref name="Champoeg"/> In Salem he would serve on the board of trustees for [[Willamette University]] before moving to [[Tillamook County]] on the Oregon coast.<ref name=salem>[http://www.salemhistory.net/people/historic_figures.htm Salem History Online: Historic figures]</ref> Prior to this in 1844, Joel Turnham threatened to hurt Hauxhurst and his wife, but was shot and killed by Deputy P.E. Pickerell before any harm could be done to the Hauxhursts.<ref>[http://www.oregonpioneers.com/1842.htm Oregon Pioneers: 1842]</ref> Then in July of 1846 the couple was divorced.<ref>[http://www.rootsweb.com/~ormultno/VR/divorce.htm Early Newspaper Divorce Notices]</ref> Webley John Hauxhurst then died in 1874.<ref name=salem/>

